observation_notes:
Megachile centuncularis belongs to the Megachile genus within the Megachilidae family. This genus is commonly referred to as "leaf cutter bees" due to the tendency of many species to cut circular or oval pieces of leaves for nest construction. However, there are exceptions within the genus; some species utilize tree resin or chewed vegetation and mud in addition to leaf fragments.

Characterized by large chewing mandibles and scopae (pollen-collecting hairs) on the underside of females' abdomens, Megachile species, including M. centuncularis, typically exhibit dark bodies with light hair bands across their abdomens in both genders. Male M. centuncularis possess unmodified forelegs and resemble females but with longer antennae and lacking scopae. Medium-sized, they typically measure between 8-11 mm in length.

Note that the true bug is actually on the leaf of a false sunflower. Paying close attention to the leaf can make all the difference. Note the difference in the leaf structure, such as the serration of the margin: a pokeweed, or a common milkweed does not exhibit this key. Keeping the phenology as is, since they match the phenology of the plant at this time of the year.

observation_notes: I can’t quite make out what the mantis is eating- maybe the fuzzy head of Bombus. I will go back and edit the species names. This is the blue holly hybrid I visited about a week ago. It is still very busy with pollinators! | Curator's Notes: It looks like arthropods might be slightly underestimated size-wise (by comparison to lef size).  Increased the following lengths: Mantis: 60 to 70, they can reach just over 11 cm (4.3 in); Monobia quadridens from 15 to 18 for which the average size (adult; length) is 15mm to 21mm (0.59" to 0.82"); Pieris rapae from 10 to 15 mm; Apis from 10 to 15 mm (10 is the lower range for workers), and it looks like it's bigger than 10 compared to flower size. Thinking the Bombus is about 12 indeed (or that flower is smaller :D). 4 mm seems low for the Lucilia (getting it at 6); finally increasing Bicyrtes quadrifasciatus (known as four-banded stink bug hunter wasp) from 14 to 19 mm, these beautiful wasps are ⅝″ to ¾″ (17 to 19 mm) long. TODO: Inform Anecdata its taxonomy is missing Bicyrtes quadrifasciatus, Monobia quadridens, and Tenodera sinensis.
___Host_plant_phenology: Breaking leaf bud // Increasing leaf size // Flowers or flower buds // Open flowers // Fruiting // Ripe fruits // Mature leaf

observation_notes: The Yellowjacket’s are not on the flowers. They are on the stems. Again there are four smaller bumblebees in the cosmos and one much larger one that seems to prefer the zinnias although it did visit the cosmos as you can see in the picture. The smaller ones spend less time at each flower than the larger bee which really works at each flower head. 67 degreesF 67% humidity and an occasional light breeze. Cosmos are in full sun. | Curator's Notes: Reviewed / Note that the big Bombus might be slightly smaller than you think. I would decrease it to 21 mm which is usually the upper average range for a queen (the biggest of the B. impatiens' casts).

observation_notes: Very small for a Bombus. | Curator's Notes: Identified fly to species. Actually, it's not that small for a Bombus. This one seems to be a worn B. impatiens. Queens and workers are generally similar in their coloring, pubescence, and structure. However, with a body length of 17–23 mm, queens have bigger bodies than males or workers. Workers have bodies 8.5–16 mm long, and males are 12–18 mm long. (Source: Williams, Paul H.; Thorp, Robbin W.; Richardson, Leif L.; Colla, Sheila R. (2014). Bumble Bees of North America: An Identification Guide. Princeton University Press.)

observation_notes: Happened to notice a surprising amount of activity in this holly while gardening. It was partly cloudy, 77 degrees and 77% humidity. | Curator's Notes: The wasp (recorded as Polistes fuscatus) is actually of 2 distinct wasps: a member of a potter and mason wasp and a dark paper wasp. Did split the record into 2: Polistes fuscatus at 18 mm (The length of P. fuscatus often ranges between 15 and 21 mm), the black wasp looks like Monobia quadridens (Four-toothed mason wasp). Discussion with Tori about the host identification (originally recorded as a European holly). There is a bit of ambiguity between the European and the American holly. There are American holly specimens in our area that are more shiny than dull. So, looking at the leaf as a secondary key. The leaf shape in the record seems closer to the American holly: leaf margins are straighter between spines than the European holly, where there is a pronounced curve between the spines.  I'll relax to genus for now until we get more firm on the identification. TODO: Inform Anecdata its taxonomy is missing the species Monobia quadridens, and the genus Ilex. (AS - set group from bees/wasps/etc to flies for Syritta)
___Host_plant_phenology: Flowers or flower buds // Open flowers // Fruiting // Ripe fruits // Mature leaf

observation_notes: The honeybees were abundant on this plant but not on any nearby flowering plants. This is the only sedum in this bed, but there are snapdragons, zinnia, cosmos, and asters nearby. It is very hot and humid today. 86 degrees F and 60% humidity. The plant was in partial sun. I saw dragonflies, butterflies, and smaller bees on nearby plants but not on the sedum. | Curator's Notes: Added 'Mature leaf' and 'Flowers or flower buds' to host phenology + set arthropod to binomial/sp. + moved the host ID from stonecrop/Sedum to stonecrop/Hylotelephium. I am not a sedum expert, but they seem to have a much smaller leaf structure than the one portrayed here. Hylotelephium is also the stonecrop family; its leaf seems closer in structure to the one I see in the record. Something to check with your group :D Keeping an eye on that record set so that we can confirm or correct it once we know more. 090723 Update: Hylotelephium confirmed.

Arthropod likely to be a B. impatiens {Pyrobombus for sure} + set length at 12 mm (size relative to the heart of the flower) + set 'developmental stage' to adult + adjusted Activity to foraging (that includes feeding + gathering pollen).
